 SERVICE DEPLOYMENT RUNBOOK
===========================

Purpose: Standardized procedure for deploying new services to the homelab. This ensures every service is properly integrated with DNS, monitoring, backups, and documentation.

==== Overview ====

This runbook is your checklist when adding ANY new service to the homelab. Following this procedure ensures:
- Service has proper DNS resolution
- Web services accessible via reverse proxy
- Monitoring and logging configured
- Backups in place
- Documentation complete
- Thoroughly tested before going live

When to use this runbook:
- Adding new Docker services (Vaultwarden, Nextcloud, Jellyfin, etc.)
- Deploying new applications
- Setting up new infrastructure components

DO NOT use this runbook for:
- Restoring existing services (see Backup Information)
- Troubleshooting broken services (see Troubleshooting Guide)
- Disaster recovery (see Disaster Recovery section)

==== Phase 1: Pre-Deployment Planning ====

Before deploying any service, answer these questions:

Service Information:
- What is the service name?
- What is the service purpose?
- Who will use this service?

Technical Requirements:
- What VM will host it? (mgmt, apps, mntr, or new VM?)
- How much RAM does it need?
- How much disk space does it need?
- What ports does it need?
- Does it need to be exposed externally? (yes/no)

Dependencies:
- Does it need a database? (PostgreSQL/MariaDB/SQLite/None)
- Does it need reverse proxy? (Nginx - yes/no)
- Does it need other services? (list)

Naming:
- What hostname will it use? ([service].lab.local)
- What container name? ([service])
- What directory for data? (/opt/docker/[service])

Resource Check:

Verify VM has resources available:

ssh jireland@[target-vm]

# Check available RAM:
free -h

# Check available disk:
df -h /opt/docker

# Check port not in use:
ss -tlnp | grep [port]

# List current containers:
docker ps

If resources insufficient, either:
- Choose different VM
- Reduce other services
- Add more resources to VM in Proxmox
- Create new VM

Document Planning Decisions:

Create deployment plan file:
nano /opt/ansible/docs/deployments/[service]-deployment-plan.txt

Service: [name]
Purpose: [description]
VM: [hostname]
Port: [port]
Hostname: [service].lab.local
Resources: [RAM]GB RAM, [disk]GB disk
Database: [type or none]
Reverse Proxy: [yes/no]
Dependencies: [list]
Deployed by: [your name]
Deployment date: [YYYY-MM-DD]

==== Phase 2: Docker Service Deployment ====

Step 1: SSH to target VM

ssh [username]@[target-vm]

Step 2: Create data directory

sudo mkdir -p /opt/docker/[service]
sudo chown [user]:[user] /opt/docker/[service]

Step 3: Create configuration files (if needed)

# Example for service with config file:
nano /opt/docker/[service]/config.yml
# Paste configuration
# Save and exit

Step 4: Add to docker-compose.yml

cd /opt/docker
nano docker-compose.yml

# Add service definition:

[service-name]:\\
  image: [image:tag]\\
  container_name: [service-name]\\
  restart: unless-stopped\\
  environment:\\
    - ENV_VAR=value\\
  volumes:\\
    - ./[service-name]:/data\\
  ports:\\
    - "[port]:[port]"\\
  networks:\\
    - homelab\\


# If service needs database, add depends_on:

  depends_on:\\
    - postgres  # or mariadb\\


Save and exit

Step 5: Validate docker-compose.yml syntax

docker compose config
# Should show parsed YAML with no errors

Step 6: Start service

docker compose up -d [service-name]

Step 7: Verify service started

docker ps | grep [service-name]
# Should show container running

Step 8: Check logs for errors

docker logs [service-name]
# Look for successful startup messages
# Watch for errors

docker logs -f [service-name]
# Follow logs in real-time (Ctrl+C to exit)

Step 9: Test service locally

curl http://localhost:[port]
# Should return response (not connection refused)

# Or for web services:
curl -I http://localhost:[port]
# Should return HTTP 200 OK

If service fails to start:
- Check docker logs for errors
- Verify port not in use: ss -tlnp | grep [port]
- Verify volume paths exist: ls -la /opt/docker/[service]
- Verify docker-compose.yml syntax: docker compose config
- Check dependencies running: docker ps

==== Phase 3: DNS Configuration ====

Step 1: SSH to FreeIPA server

ssh [user]@mgmt.lab.local

Step 2: Authenticate as admin

kinit admin
# Enter admin password

Step 3: Add DNS A record

ipa dnsrecord-add lab.local [service-name] –a-rec=[VM-IP]

Example:
ipa dnsrecord-add lab.local vault –a-rec=192.168.1.12

Step 4: Verify DNS resolution

nslookup [service].lab.local
# Should return correct IP address

# Test from another machine:
ping [service].lab.local
# Should resolve and respond

DNS IP Reference:
- mgmt.lab.local: x.x.x.x
- apps.lab.local: x.x.x.x
- mntr.lab.local: x.x.x.x

If DNS doesn't resolve:
- Check FreeIPA DNS service: systemctl status named-pkcs11
- Verify record created: ipa dnsrecord-show lab.local [service-name]
- Check client using FreeIPA DNS: cat /etc/resolv.conf (should show 192.168.1.11)

==== Phase 4: Reverse Proxy Configuration ====

Only for web-based services that need external access

Skip this phase if:
- Service is not web-based
- Service accessed via IP:port directly
- Service is internal-only (like database)

Step 1: SSH to apps VM (where Nginx runs)

ssh [user]@apps.lab.local

Step 2: Edit Nginx configuration

cd /opt/docker/nginx
nano nginx.conf

Step 3: Add server block

# Add before the closing brace:

  server {\\
      listen 443;\\
      server_name [service].lab.local;\\
      \\
      location / {\\
          proxy_pass http://[container-name]:[port];\\
          proxy_set_header Host $host;\\
          proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;\\
          proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;\\
          proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;\\
      }\\
  }\\


Example:

  server {\\
      listen 443;\\
      server_name vault.lab.local;\\
      \\
      location / {\\
          proxy_pass http://vaultwarden:80;\\
          proxy_set_header Host $host;\\
          proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;\\
      }\\
  }\\


Save and exit

Step 4: Test Nginx configuration

docker exec nginx nginx -t
# Should show: syntax is ok, test is successful

Step 5: Reload Nginx

docker compose restart nginx

Step 6: Verify routing works

curl -I http://[service].lab.local
# Should return HTTP 200 OK

# From browser:
http://[service].lab.local
# Should load service

If Nginx fails:
- Check syntax: docker exec nginx nginx -t
- Check Nginx logs: docker logs nginx
- Verify service reachable: curl http://[container]:[port] from Nginx container
- Check server_name matches DNS record

==== Phase 5: Monitoring Integration ====

Step 1: Determine monitoring needs

Does service export Prometheus metrics?
- Check service documentation
- Common metrics endpoints: /metrics, /api/metrics

Does service need log shipping?
- Yes for critical services
- No for non-critical or rarely-used services

Step 2: Add to Prometheus (if service has metrics)

ssh [user]@mntr.lab.local
cd /opt/docker
nano prometheus.yml

# Add under scrape_configs:

    job_name: '[service-name]'

static_configs:

    targets: ['[VM-IP]:[metrics-port]']

labels:

        instance: '[service].lab.local'\\


Example:

    job_name: 'vaultwarden'

static_configs:

    targets: ['x.x.x.x:PORT#']

labels:

        instance: 'vault.lab.local'\\


Save and exit

docker compose restart prometheus

Step 3: Verify metrics collection

# Open Prometheus UI:
http://prometheus.lab.local/targets

# Look for new target, should show “UP” status

Step 4: Configure Promtail (if shipping logs)

Promtail already configured on all VMs to ship:
- /var/log/auth.log
- /var/log/syslog

For application-specific logs:

ssh [user]@[target-vm]
sudo nano /etc/promtail/promtail-config.yml

# Add new scrape config:

    job_name: [service]

static_configs:

    targets:
        localhost

labels:

        job: [service]\\
        host: [hostname]\\
        __path__: /opt/docker/[service]/logs/*.log\\


Save and exit

sudo systemctl restart promtail

Step 5: Verify logs appearing in Loki

# Open Grafana:
http://grafana.lab.local

# Navigate to Explore
# Select Loki data source
# Query: {job=“[service]”}
# Should show logs

If monitoring not working:
- Prometheus: Check targets page for errors
- Check firewall: sudo firewall-cmd –list-ports (Rocky) or sudo ufw status (Ubuntu)
- Promtail: Check status: sudo systemctl status promtail
- Check Promtail logs: sudo journalctl -u promtail -f

==== Phase 6: Backup Configuration ====

Step 1: Identify what needs backup

Critical data locations:
- Database dumps (if service uses database)
- Configuration files (/opt/docker/[service]/config.*)
- User data (/opt/docker/[service]/data or similar)
- Application state

Do NOT backup:
- Cache directories
- Temporary files
- Log files (unless critical audit logs)
- Docker images (re-downloadable)

Step 2: Test manual backup

ssh [user]@[target-vm]

# For file-based data:
tar -czf /tmp/test-backup.tar.gz /opt/docker/[service]
ls -lh /tmp/test-backup.tar.gz
# Should show non-zero file size

# For database-backed service:
docker exec postgres pg_dump -U [user] [database] > /tmp/test-backup.sql
# or
docker exec mariadb mysqldump -u [user] -p[password] [database] > /tmp/test-backup.sql

ls -lh /tmp/test-backup.sql
# Should show non-zero file size

# Clean up test:
rm /tmp/test-backup.*

Step 3: Add to backup playbook

ssh [user]@mgmt.lab.local
nano /opt/ansible/playbooks/backup-homelab.yml

# Add task in appropriate section:

    name: Backup [service] data

archive:

      path: /opt/docker/[service]\\
      dest: /opt/backups/[service]-{{ timestamp }}.tar.gz\\
    delegate_to: [target-vm]\\


# For database-backed services:

    name: Backup [service] database

shell: docker exec [db-container] [dump-command] > /opt/backups/[service]-db-timestamp.sql

    delegate_to: [target-vm]\\


# Add cleanup task:

    name: Clean old [service] backups

find:

      paths: /opt/backups\\
      patterns: "[service]-*.tar.gz"\\
      age: 7d\\
    register: old_backups\\
    delegate_to: [target-vm]\\


    name: Delete old [service] backups

file:

      path: "{{ item.path }}"\\
      state: absent\\
    loop: "{{ old_backups.files }}"\\
    delegate_to: [target-vm]\\


Save and exit

Step 4: Test backup playbook

cd /opt/ansible/playbooks
ansible-playbook backup-homelab.yml

# Check backup created:
ssh [user]@[target-vm]
ls -lh /opt/backups/[service]-*

Step 5: Document restore procedure

Create restore documentation:
nano /opt/ansible/docs/restore/[service]-restore.txt

Service: [name]
Backup location: /opt/backups/[service]-*.tar.gz

Restore procedure:
1. Stop service: docker compose stop [service]
2. Remove old data: rm -rf /opt/docker/[service]/*
3. Extract backup: tar -xzf /opt/backups/[service]-[date].tar.gz -C /
4. Start service: docker compose up -d [service]
5. Verify: docker logs [service]

For database restore:
1. Stop service: docker compose stop [service]
2. Restore database: docker exec -i [db] [restore-command] < backup.sql
3. Start service: docker compose up -d [service]

Save and exit

Step 6: Test restore procedure

# On test/non-critical service only
# Follow documented restore procedure
# Verify service works after restore

