==== Rollback Procedure ====

If deployment fails or causes issues:

Step 1: Stop service immediately

ssh [user]@[target-vm]
docker compose stop [service]

Step 2: Remove from docker-compose.yml

nano /opt/docker/docker-compose.yml
# Comment out or remove service definition
# Save and exit

Step 3: Remove DNS record

ssh [user]@mgmt.lab.local
kinit admin
ipa dnsrecord-del lab.local [service] –a-rec=[IP]

Step 4: Remove Nginx config (if added)

ssh [user]@apps.lab.local
nano /opt/docker/nginx/nginx.conf
# Remove server block
# Save and exit
docker compose restart nginx

Step 5: Remove from monitoring

ssh [user]@mntr.lab.local
nano /opt/docker/prometheus.yml
# Remove scrape config
# Save and exit
docker compose restart prometheus

Step 6: Document rollback

Update Change Log:
[YYYY-MM-DD] - Rolled back [Service Name]
- Reason: [why]
- Issues encountered: [describe]
- Lessons learned: [list]

Step 7: Clean up data (optional)

# Only if not planning to retry:
ssh [user]@[target-vm]
sudo rm -rf /opt/docker/[service]

==== Common Deployment Scenarios ====

Scenario 1: Simple Web Application (No Database)

Example: Static file server, dashboard, monitoring tool

Phases required:
- Phase 1: Planning ✓
- Phase 2: Docker Deployment ✓
- Phase 3: DNS ✓
- Phase 4: Reverse Proxy ✓
- Phase 5: Monitoring (optional) ✓
- Phase 6: Backup ✓
- Phase 7: Documentation ✓
- Phase 8: Testing ✓

Estimated time: 1-2 hours

Scenario 2: Application with Database

Example: Gitea, WordPress, Nextcloud

Additional considerations:
- Database must be deployed first (or already exist)
- Add depends_on in docker-compose.yml
- Backup both application data AND database
- Test database connection before going live

Phases required: All phases
Estimated time: 2-3 hours

Scenario 3: Internal Service (No External Access)

Example: Database, cache, internal API

Phases to skip:
- Phase 4: Reverse Proxy (not needed)

Phases required: All others
Estimated time: 1-2 hours

Scenario 4: Background Service (No Web UI)

Example: Backup service, monitoring agent, cron jobs

Phases to skip:
- Phase 3: DNS (maybe - depends on service)
- Phase 4: Reverse Proxy (not needed)

Phases required: All others
Estimated time: 1 hour

==== Tips & Best Practices ====

Planning:
- Always plan before deploying
- Document decisions before executing
- Check resource availability first
- Review similar services for patterns

Deployment:
- Deploy during low-usage times
- Start with minimal configuration
- Test locally before exposing externally
- Keep initial deployment simple

Testing:
- Test thoroughly before announcing
- Verify data persistence (restart test)
- Test from multiple clients
- Have rollback plan ready

Documentation:
- Document as you deploy (not after)
- Include troubleshooting notes
- Document credentials securely
- Update related documentation

Monitoring:
- Add monitoring from day 1
- Watch closely for first 48 hours
- Set up alerts (when Phase 4.2 complete)
- Review resource usage weekly

Backups:
- Configure backups before going live
- Test restore procedure
- Verify backup file validity
- Keep backups for 7+ days

==== Quick Reference ====

Full deployment workflow:

1. Plan (decide VM, port, hostname, resources)
2. Deploy (add to docker-compose.yml, start container)
3. DNS (add A record in FreeIPA)
4. Proxy (add Nginx server block if web service)
5. Monitor (add to Prometheus/Promtail)
6. Backup (add to backup playbook, test)
7. Document (Service Catalog, Change Log)
8. Test (DNS, access, persistence, monitoring, backup)
9. Launch (announce, monitor)

Critical paths:
- Docker → DNS → Proxy → Test → Live
- Docker → Monitoring → Backup → Test → Live

Never skip:
- Testing (Phase 8)
- Documentation (Phase 7)
- Backups (Phase 6)
